&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-revocation/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-revocation/> ;
  schema:name "Revocation" ;
  schema:description "A Revocation is a triple (Q, G, B) — a principal Q who granted authority G to beneficiary B — together with a retraction act ρ that removes G from B's operative domain and restores it to Q's exclusive domain. The defining structure: revocation is the left inverse of delegation; it retracts the sub-presheaf H_G ↪ H_Q that was shared with B, collapsing B's claim on G back to ⊥. Three cases: full revocation (entire grant withdrawn), partial revocation (sub-grant G' ⊆ G withdrawn while G  G' remains), and conditional revocation (withdrawal triggered by B's breach or changed circumstances). Revocation is always unilateral by Q — it does not require B's consent. Formally: a sub-presheaf retraction, the left inverse of the inclusion morphism that constituted the delegation." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:isPartOf &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/> ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-revocation/> ;
  rdfs:seeAlso "Delegation, Principal, Authority, Investiture, HohfeldianPosition, Breach, Contract, Trust" ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-revocation/> .

